# Kotlin: KDoc, Testing & Safety

## Public API KDoc

Every public declaration (class, function, property) needs KDoc. Document params, return
value, error/failure behavior, and link to the relevant spec (BIP/CIP/RFC). Validators
must say **"structural validation only"** in KDoc — never imply an address exists or
is spendable.

```kotlin
/**
 * Decodes a Bech32-encoded string into its human-readable part and data payload.
 *
 * Performs structural validation only. Does not verify that the address exists
 * on-chain, is owned, or is spendable.
 *
 * @param input the Bech32-encoded string (e.g. "addr_test1...").
 * @return [KardanoResult.Ok] with [Bech32Decoded] on success, or [KardanoResult.Err] with
 *   [Bech32Error] if the checksum, characters, length, or HRP are invalid. Never throws on
 *   malformed input.
 * @see <a href="https://github.com/bitcoin/bips/blob/master/bip-0173.mediawiki">BIP-173</a>
 */
public fun decodeBech32(input: String): KardanoResult<Bech32Decoded, Bech32Error>
```

## Error policy

- Public APIs that can fail return a **sealed error or the SDK's `KardanoResult` type** —
  no throwing. Do not name the SDK type `Result` (avoids confusion with `kotlin.Result`).
- Any unavoidable thrower must be annotated `@Throws` and documented in KDoc.
- Never let an exception cross the Swift/ObjC boundary — it crashes iOS.

## ByteArray correctness

```kotlin
// BAD — reference equality
require(a == b)

// GOOD — value equality
require(a.contentEquals(b))
```

- Defensive copy on construction and from every accessor.
- Never expose a mutable internal `ByteArray`.
- Override `equals` / `hashCode` using `contentEquals` / `contentHashCode`.

## Tests

Every primitive/encoding/parser/validator change needs tests covering **valid**,
**invalid**, and **edge** cases (empty, max length, boundary bytes, bad checksum/chars,
truncated input, nesting limits).

Round-trip: `decode(encode(x)) == x` is safe to test. Testing `encode(decode(y)) == y`
must not silently accept non-canonical input — if used, also test that non-canonical
input is rejected before decoding.

**Never invent test vectors.** Authoritative vectors must be copied verbatim from:
- Bech32/Bech32m — BIP-173, BIP-350.
- CBOR — RFC 8949 Appendix A.
- Addresses — CIP-19.

Cite the source URL in a comment above each fixture block. Never weaken a validator to
make a test pass.

## Parser safety

- Never allocate from an untrusted length field (`ByteArray(untrustedLen)` is unsafe).
- Define named limit constants (`MAX_INPUT_BYTES`, `MAX_NESTING_DEPTH`,
  `MAX_COLLECTION_ELEMENTS`) and reject inputs that exceed them.
- Reject non-canonical or unsupported encodings explicitly.
- Reject out-of-range numeric values; never truncate silently.
